{"id":"fe7c74dc-54d8-4602-ac7a-7bd13525c712","title":"1507/01/31: footnote","type":"main-list-block","children":[{"id":"54f7c8b0-9800-4259-83bd-e63ac51132aa","type":"standoff-editor-block","text":"The Michele mentioned in this letter is Michele di Piero di Pippo, a stone cutter of Settignano, who was sent to Carrara in connection with the marbles for the facade of San Lorenzo in Florence. With regard to the \u0022Madonna\u0022 mentioned further on, it is not certain whether Michelangelo refers to the marble bas-relief now preserved in the Casa Buonarroti in Florence or to the Madonna and Child which is the chief treasure of Notre Dame at Bruges. In passing, it may be worth while to draw attention to the obvious nervousness which marks all Michelangelo\u0027s financial transactions. The instructions with regard to the banker at Lucca are characteristic, and afford sufficient proof of the artist\u0027s aversion to trusting his money in the hands of other people.","standoffProperties":[{"id":"da97f186-440d-4eb2-8c3a-2143c3c1a4c9","type":"page","start":0,"end":104,"value":"31","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"391c9afa-d95d-4b69-95ab-6c28b174317d","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":4,"end":10,"value":"a8456bac-071b-4477-9868-e54769ec43c8","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"2319298b-34e6-46f0-ab5a-91f69fe6a3ca","type":"codex/document-reference","start":30,"end":35,"value":"9d7f3de9-44d5-46f0-8e01-e74f16bd0c95","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"73b24322-2886-4f59-97b3-bbd2a584a4a3","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":40,"end":64,"value":"a8456bac-071b-4477-9868-e54769ec43c8","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"e48f45be-bf61-43ac-9a8e-7b48b60c4cd1","type":"codex/trait-reference","start":69,"end":80,"value":"460f7023-9a29-44c5-8c04-8cc2877d22a7","zeroPoint":false,"metadata":[]},{"id":"d45352f2-f7a5-4c47-a92b-c10eb5891f88","type":"codex/entity-reference","start":85,"end":94,"value":"93f44085-a759-46d1-924c-439e1f3a431e","zeroPoint":false,"metada